using SkiaSharp;

const int width = 100;
const int height = 100;

var linearColorSpace = SKColorSpace.CreateSrgbLinear();
var linearInfo = new SKImageInfo(width, height, SKColorType.Rgba8888, SKAlphaType.Premul, linearColorSpace);
using var linearBitmap = new SKBitmap(linearInfo);

using (var canvas = new SKCanvas(linearBitmap))
{
    using var paint = new SKPaint();
    paint.Color = new SKColor(200, 50, 50, 255);
    canvas.DrawRect(0, 0, width, height, paint);
}

Console.WriteLine($"Source bitmap color space is linear: {linearBitmap.ColorSpace?.GammaIsLinear}");

using var image = SKImage.FromBitmap(linearBitmap);

var buggyDestInfo = new SKImageInfo(width, height, SKColorType.Rgba8888, SKAlphaType.Premul);
using var buggyBitmap = new SKBitmap(buggyDestInfo);
image.ReadPixels(buggyDestInfo, buggyBitmap.GetPixels());

var correctDestInfo = new SKImageInfo(width, height, SKColorType.Rgba8888, SKAlphaType.Premul, SKColorSpace.CreateSrgb());
using var correctBitmap = new SKBitmap(correctDestInfo);
image.ReadPixels(correctDestInfo, correctBitmap.GetPixels());

var buggyPixel = buggyBitmap.GetPixel(50, 50);
var correctPixel = correctBitmap.GetPixel(50, 50);

Console.WriteLine();
Console.WriteLine($"Buggy (null colorspace dest) pixel:   R={buggyPixel.Red}, G={buggyPixel.Green}, B={buggyPixel.Blue}, A={buggyPixel.Alpha}");
Console.WriteLine($"Correct (sRGB colorspace dest) pixel: R={correctPixel.Red}, G={correctPixel.Green}, B={correctPixel.Blue}, A={correctPixel.Alpha}");

bool colorsMatch = buggyPixel.Red == correctPixel.Red && buggyPixel.Green == correctPixel.Green && buggyPixel.Blue == correctPixel.Blue;

Console.WriteLine();
if (colorsMatch)
    Console.WriteLine("SUCCESS: Colors match - no color space conversion issue detected");
else
{
    Console.WriteLine("BUG REPRODUCED: Colors differ - null colorspace destination skips conversion");
    Console.WriteLine($"  Expected (sRGB converted): R={correctPixel.Red}, G={correctPixel.Green}, B={correctPixel.Blue}");
    Console.WriteLine($"  Got (raw linear values):   R={buggyPixel.Red}, G={buggyPixel.Green}, B={buggyPixel.Blue}");
}

proposedResponse.body:
We've confirmed this issue. The reported behavior reproduces on macOS arm64 with SkiaSharp 2.88.3, 3.119.2, and the current main branch.

**Root cause:** The platform conversion methods (`ToWriteableBitmap`, `ToBitmap`, `ToCGImage`) create a destination `SKImageInfo` with `null` color space via `new SKImageInfo(width, height)`. When `ReadPixels` is called with a null-colorspace destination, Skia copies raw pixel values without color space conversion. For linear color space bitmaps, this produces significantly darker output (e.g., sRGB `(200, 50, 50)` becomes `(147, 8, 8)`).

**Tested versions:**
| Version | Result |
|---------|--------|
| 2.88.3 (reported) | ❌ Reproduced |
| 3.119.2 (latest) | ❌ Reproduced |
| main (source) | ❌ Reproduced |

**Workaround:** Convert the bitmap to sRGB before assigning to `SKBitmapImageSource`:
```csharp
var displayInfo = new SKImageInfo(bitmap.Width, bitmap.Height,
    SKImageInfo.PlatformColorType,
    SKAlphaType.Premul,
    SKColorSpace.CreateSrgb());
var displayBitmap = new SKBitmap(displayInfo);
using (var canvas = new SKCanvas(displayBitmap))
{
    canvas.DrawBitmap(bitmap, 0, 0);
}
var imageSource = new SKBitmapImageSource { Bitmap = displayBitmap };
```

This is related to #2354 (same color space unawareness in `GetPixel`).
